{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-baad3e6c9843b844", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tBlack-Box Optimization for Identifying and\n2\tInverting Audio Dynamic Range Control Effects\n3\tHaoran Sun\n4\tDominique Fourer\n5\tHichem Maaref\n6\tIBISC (EA 4526), Univ. Évry Paris-Saclay\n7\t\n8\tarXiv:2607.19645v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n9\t\n10\tJuly 23, 2026\n11\tAbstract\n12\tDynamic Range Compression (DRC) is a widely used nonlinear audio\n13\teffect whose parameters are often unknown, making blind estimation and\n14\tinversion challenging. In this work, we formulate DRC parameter estimation as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptually motivated\n15\tfeature space. Given an observed signal and a reference representation, we\n16\testimate the parameters that minimize the distance between feature descriptors of the reconstructed and reference signals. Unlike gradient-based\n17\tapproaches, the proposed method does not require differentiability of the\n18\tDRC model or the feature extraction pipeline, enabling the use of nonlinear and histogram-based descriptors. Experimental results demonstrate\n19\tthat the proposed method achieves competitive performance in blind parameter estimation and dry signal recovery, outperforming or matching\n20\tstate-of-the-art models in terms of reconstruction quality.\n21\t\n22\t1\n23\t\n24\tIntroduction\n25\t\n26\tThe estimation of audio processor parameters from observed signals is an important topic in audio signal processing, with applications ranging from audio\n27\trestoration and remixing to effect modeling and analysis [1]. In particular,\n28\tthe inversion of Dynamic Range Control (DRC) remains a challenging problem\n29\tdue to its highly nonlinear, time-dependent, and often non-invertible nature.\n30\tThese properties make the recovery of both the original signal and the underlying compression parameters inherently ambiguous, especially in blind settings\n31\twhere only the processed signal is available.\n32\tRecent works have explored data-driven approaches for audio effect parameter estimation. For instance, [2] proposes an autoencoder framework combined\n33\twith differentiable digital signal processing (DDSP) modules to estimate effect\n34\tparameters in an end-to-end manner. Extending this paradigm, [3] introduces\n35\t\n36\t1\n37\t\n38\t\fprobabilistic models that capture parameter uncertainty by predicting distributions instead of point estimates. Similarly, hybrid approaches combining deep\n39\tlearning and signal processing have been proposed for DRC inversion [4].\n40\tIn such approaches, the use of differentiable signal processing blocks allows gradient-based optimization of audio parameters. This approach has been\n41\tsuccessfully applied to various audio effects, including equalization and style\n42\ttransfer [5–7]. More generally, differentiable formulations of signal processing\n43\toperators have enabled efficient parameter estimation within end-to-end learning frameworks.\n44\tHowever, these approaches rely on the differentiability of both the signal\n45\tprocessing chain and the objective function. In practice, this assumption may\n46\tnot hold when the evaluation is performed in perceptually motivated feature\n47\tspaces, which often involve nonlinear and non-differentiable operations such\n48\tas histogram-based descriptors or handcrafted audio features. In such cases,\n49\tgradient-based optimization becomes inapplicable or unreliable.\n50\tIn this work, we propose to formulate the estimation of DRC parameters\n51\tas a black-box optimization problem [8]. The objective function is defined as a\n52\tdistance in a feature space between a reference representation and the output\n53\tof a parametric inverse DRC model. This formulation does not require differentiability and enables the use of derivative-free optimization methods. The main\n54\tcontributions of this work are as follows:\n55\t• We propose a novel formulation of blind DRC parameter estimation and\n56\teffect inversion as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptual feature\n57\tspace.\n58\t• We identify a perceptually motivated feature space suitable for capturing the effects of dynamic range. In particular, we show that dynamic\n59\thistogram descriptors can provide an effective optimization space.\n60\t• We propose a derivative-free optimization approach that can estimate perceptually plausible parameters without requiring differentiable models.\n61\t\n62\t2\n63\t\n64\tRelated Work\n65\t\n66\tModel-based inversion: Blind estimation of audio effect parameters has been\n67\taddressed using model-based, data-driven, and hybrid approaches. Classical\n68\tdigital audio effects and their analytical formulations are detailed in [9, 10].\n69\tEarly inversion methods exploit explicit knowledge of the processor equations\n70\tto recover the original signal or estimate effect parameters. For example, Gorlow\n71\tand Reiss [11] proposed a model-based inversion framework for dynamic range\n72\tcompression assuming complete knowledge of the compressor structure. While\n73\tphysically interpretable, such approaches are limited to scenarios where the\n74\tprocessing model is fully specified.\n75\tNeural effect parameter estimation and modeling: Recent work\n76\tmainly uses deep learning to model audio effects and to estimate their parameters. SignalTrain [12] and the recurrent architecture proposed by Wright\n77\t2\n78\t\n79\t\fet al. [13] focused on black-box emulation of nonlinear audio processors from\n80\tinput-output examples, whereas Sheng and Fazekas [14] addressed the related\n81\ttask of compressor parameter estimation using a siamese feature-learning architecture. They showed that neural networks can accurately emulate nonlinear\n82\taudio processors from input–output examples without requiring explicit knowledge of their internal structure. More recently, supervised neural approaches\n83\thave been proposed for blind audio effect parameter estimation [2, 4], while\n84\tprobabilistic formulations have been investigated to model ambiguities inherent\n85\tto inverse problems [3].\n86\tDifferentiable Digital Signal Processing: In parallel, Differentiable Digital Signal Processing (DDSP) enables the integration of signal processing algorithms into end-to-end trainable neural networks [15]. This paradigm has\n87\tbeen extended to differentiable audio effect modeling, virtual analog systems,\n88\tand audio style transfer [5–7, 16, 17]. In particular, Ramírez et al. [18] proposed DeepAFx, which combines differentiable DSP with simultaneous perturbation stochastic approximation (SPSA) to optimize the parameters of nondifferentiable audio effects. While these methods exploit differentiable processing chains or gradient approximations, they generally assume optimization in\n89\tthe signal domain or a differentiable objective function.\n90\tPositioning of our work: Our work differs from previous approaches in\n91\ttwo important aspects. First, rather than learning a forward model of the\n92\tcompressor or directly regressing its parameters, we formulate blind compressor\n93\tparameter estimation as a derivative-free optimization problem in a perceptually\n94\tmotivated feature space.\n95\tSecond, instead of relying on differentiable signal processing and gradientbased optimization, the objective function is evaluated in a feature space containing non-differentiable dynamic histogram descriptors. This makes gradientbased optimization inapplicable and motivates the use of black-box optimization. By combining a model-based inverse compressor with derivative-free optimization, our framework bridges model-based inversion and learning-based\n96\tparameter estimation.\n97\t\n98\t3\n99\t\n100\tProblem Formulation\n101\t\n102\t3.1\n103\t\n104\tOverview\n105\t\n106\tWe consider the blind estimation of dynamic range compressor (DRC) parameters from an observed signal:\n107\ty = DRC(x, θ),\n108\t\n109\t(1)\n110\t\n111\twhere x denotes the unknown dry signal and θ the unknown DRC parameter\n112\tvector. Since neither the original signal nor the compressor parameters are\n113\tavailable, recovering θ from y is an ill-posed inverse problem, as multiple combinations of dry signals and compressor parameters may produce perceptually\n114\tsimilar observations.\n115\t3\n116\t\n117\t\f,\n118\t\n119\tEnvelope\n120\tDetection\n121\t\n122\tStatic Curve\n123\tComputation\n124\t\n125\t,\n126\t\n127\t,\n128\t\n129\tGain Filter\n130\tSmoothing\n131\t\n132\t,\n133\t\n134\tFigure 1: Illustration of a dynamic range controller.\n135\tRather than jointly estimating the dry signal x and the DRC parameters θ,\n136\twe exploit the availability of a model-based DRC inversion operator [11]. Given\n137\ta candidate parameter vector θ, the inverse model produces a reconstructed dry\n138\tsignal:\n139\tx̂(θ) = DRC−1 (y, θ).\n140\t\n141\t(2)\n142\t\n143\tThe quality of this reconstruction is assessed in a perceptually motivated\n144\tfeature space. Let ϕ(·) denote a perceptually motivated feature extractor and\n145\tlet ϕref be a reference feature vector representing the expected characteristics\n146\tof dry signals. Parameter estimation is formulated as the optimization problem:\n147\t\u0001\u0001\n148\tθ̂ = arg min ds ϕref , ϕ DRC−1 (y, θ) ,\n149\t(3)\n150\tθ∈Θ\n151\t\n152\twhere ds (·, ·) denotes a distance in the feature space.\n153\tOnce the parameters have been estimated, the recovered dry signal is obtained as\n154\tx̂(θ̂) = DRC−1 (y, θ̂).\n155\t\n156\t3.2\n157\t\n158\t(4)\n159\t\n160\tDynamic Range Control\n161\t\n162\tDynamic Range Control (DRC) reduces the dynamic range of a signal by attenuating high-amplitude components while leaving low-level components mostly\n163\tunchanged (compression); or increases the dynamic range by attenuating lowamplitude components while leaving high-level components mostly unchanged\n164\t(expansion) [10]. This results in a more controlled signal amplitude and is commonly used in music production, broadcasting, and audio mastering.\n165\tFormally, DRC is a nonlinear, time-dependent transformation that modifies\n166\tan input signal x[n] (assumed real-valued and discrete, with sampling frequency\n167\tFs ) through a time-varying gain function g[n]:\n168\ty[n] = DRC (x, θ) = x[n] gx,θ [n],\n169\t\n170\t4\n171\t\n172\t(5)\n173\t\n174\t\fwhere θ denotes the set of compressor parameters. A typical DRC model [9]\n175\t(cf. Fig. 1) is parameterized by:\n176\tθ = {L, R, τvatt , τvrel , τgatt , τgrel , p},\n177\twhere L is the threshold (in dB), R is the compression ratio, τvatt and τvrel are\n178\tthe attack and release times for the envelope detector, τgatt and τgrel are the\n179\tattack and release times for gain smoothing, and p defines the detection type\n180\t(e.g., peak or RMS).\n181\tThe computation of the gain g[n] is typically performed in three stages including the detection envelope, the computation of the static compression curve\n182\tand the gain smoothing. The compressed (wet) signal is finally obtained using\n183\tEq. (5).\n184\t\n185\t3.3\n186\t\n187\tBlind Parameter Estimation and DRC Inversion\n188\t\n189\tThe inversion of dynamic range compression aims to recover the original signal\n190\tx that produced the observed compressed signal y. Blind configurations, where\n191\tthe DRC parameters are unknown, are challenging, but can be addressed using\n192\tdata-driven approaches. In particular, hybrid strategies combining deep neural\n193\tnetworks with model-based inversion have been proposed [4]. These methods\n194\ttypically rely on neural architectures, such as Audio Spectrogram Transformers\n195\tor effect encoders [2, 19], to estimate DRC parameters, which are then used\n196\twithin a signal processing model for inversion. In this work, the model-based\n197\tinversion is based on the model proposed in [11] and extended in [4]. This approach assumes that the inverse model is parameterized by θ, which is estimated\n198\tfrom the observed signal in order to perform inversion (cf. Eq. (4)).\n199\t\n200\t4\n201\t\n202\tFeature Space and Black-Box Optimization\n203\t\n204\t4.1\n205\t\n206\tPerceptually motivated audio features\n207\t\n208\tOur work is based on the audio quality features 1 introduced in [20] to describe\n209\tthe perceptual impact of audio processing chains. These features are effective\n210\tfor tasks such as predicting the type of dynamic range compression and the\n211\tproduction decade of audio mixtures, suggesting that they encode meaningful information related to compression artifacts and dynamic structure. This\n212\twork uses a subset of these features, with particular emphasis on the dynamic\n213\thistogram (DH), which captures the distribution of signal amplitudes and is\n214\tdirectly influenced by dynamic range compression.\n215\tThe proposed feature set combines complementary descriptors that capture\n216\tdynamic, spectral, and perceptual properties of the signal. It includes energyrelated measures (RMS, peak, crest factor), spectral descriptors (centroid, bandwidth, and statistics of the average spectrum), and perceptual stereo features\n217\t(e.g., spectral entropy, background noise level, inter-channel correlation).\n218\t1 https://github.com/dfourer/AQFeatures/\n219\t\n220\t5\n221\t\n222\t\fIn addition, we use distribution-based descriptors derived from the dynamic\n223\thistogram (DH), which characterizes the amplitude distribution over time. From\n224\tthis histogram, we extract eight summary statistics (mean, peak value, peak position, centroid, median, entropy, standard deviation, and skewness), labeled as\n225\tDH1–DH8, which are particularly sensitive to the redistribution of signal levels\n226\tinduced by compression. All descriptors are concatenated into a single feature\n227\tvector. Since many of these features involve nonlinear and non-differentiable\n228\toperations, this motivates the use of black-box optimization methods.\n229\t\n230\t4.2\n231\t\n232\tFeature Space Selection\n233\t\n234\tBecause no ground-truth optimization criterion is available for blind inversion,\n235\twe evaluate candidate feature spaces using a proxy criterion measuring whether\n236\tinversion consistently moves signals closer to the dry reference. Hence, for assessing the relevance of a feature space for inversion, we introduce a success rate\n237\t(SR) criterion that evaluates whether the reconstructed signal is closer to the\n238\treference signal than the corresponding processed signal.\n239\tGiven a reference signal x, we generate processed signals y i = DRC(x, θi )\n240\tand corresponding reconstructions x̂i = DRC−1 (y i , θi ). Hence, a feature space\n241\tis considered effective if:\n242\t\u0001\n243\t\u0001\n244\td ϕ(x̂i ), ϕ(x) < d ϕ(y i ), ϕ(x) ,\n245\t(6)\n246\twhere d denotes the Euclidean distance in the feature space.\n247\tThe success rate is defined as\n248\tSR =\n249\t\n250\tN\n251\t\u0001\n252\t\u0001\u0001\n253\t1 X\n254\t1 d ϕ(x̂i ), ϕ(x) < d ϕ(yi ), ϕ(x) ,\n255\tN i=1\n256\t\n257\t(7)\n258\t\n259\twhere N is the number of samples and 1(·) is the indicator function that returns\n260\t1 if the condition holds and 0 otherwise. A higher success rate indicates that\n261\tthe feature space better reflects reconstruction quality relative to the processed\n262\tsignal.\n263\t\n264\t4.3\n265\t\n266\tBlack-box optimization\n267\t\n268\tThe problem of DRC parameter estimation from the observed signal y is formulated as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptually relevant feature space. Following Eq. (3), the estimated parameter vector θ̂ minimizes\n269\tthe distance between the reconstructed signal and a reference representation\n270\tϕref ≈ ϕ(x):\n271\t\u0001\n272\t\u0001\n273\tθ̂ = arg min d ϕ DRC−1 (y; θ) , ϕref .\n274\t(8)\n275\tθ\n276\t\n277\tSince the objective function involves nonlinear and non-differentiable operations (e.g., feature extraction and statistical descriptors), gradient-based optimization methods are not applicable.\n278\t\n279\t6\n280\t\n281\t\fTo improve robustness, the optimization is performed in a normalized parameter space. The physical parameter bounds θmin and θmax are derived from\n282\tthe admissible ranges of the considered processing model. A normalized parameter vector z ∈ [0, 1]6 is then mapped to the corresponding physical parameters\n283\tθ.\n284\tWe further incorporate a prior estimate θ̂0 , obtained using a data-driven\n285\tDRC parameter estimator [4], by introducing a regularization term. The final\n286\tobjective is defined as:\n287\t\u0001\n288\tL(θ; y) = d ϕ(DRC −1 (y, θ)), ϕref + µ θ − θ̂0\n289\t\n290\t.\n291\t\n292\t(9)\n293\t\n294\t2\n295\t\n296\twhere ∥.∥2 denotes the ℓ2 -norm.\n297\tIn this study, we consider two distinct black-box optimization methods: Pattern Search [21] and Bayesian Optimization [22]. After optimization, the estimated parameters θ̂ are used within the inverse DRC model to reconstruct the\n298\tsignal x̂.\n299\t\n300\t5\n301\t\n302\tNumerical Results\n303\t\n304\t5.1\n305\t\n306\tDataset\n307\t\n308\tWe use audio material from the MedleyDB dataset [23].\n309\tBased on the available metadata, we select dry mixture signals from five\n310\tmusical genres: classical, rock, electronic, pop, and jazz. For each genre, five\n311\t30-second excerpts are randomly sampled from distinct recordings, resulting in\n312\ta total of 25 original signals. All excerpts are converted to mono by averaging\n313\tthe stereo channels.\n314\tCompression, expansion, and the corresponding model-based inversion are\n315\tperformed using the framework proposed in [4]. Each signal is processed using\n316\t30 predefined DRC profiles, whose parameter ranges are detailed in Table 1.\n317\tThis yields a total of 750 processed samples of 30 seconds for each task.\n318\t\n319\t5.2\n320\t\n321\tFeature space selection\n322\t\n323\tTable 2 presents the top-ranked features for compression and expansion. In both\n324\tcases, the same three features from the dynamic histogram, DH1, DH4, and DH5,\n325\tachieve the highest scores. We therefore select these three features to define the\n326\tfinal feature space for the subsequent experiments.\n327\tFigure 2 shows the projection of all five musical styles into the selected threedimensional feature space. Compression and expansion are displayed separately.\n328\tIn both cases, the processed signals move away from the original references,\n329\twhile the recovered signals tend to remain closer to them. This observation\n330\tis confirmed by the average distance to the original signal, denoted d¯ that is\n331\tsmaller. This effect is more pronounced for compression, where the decompressed points nearly overlap with the original cluster along most of the main\n332\t\n333\t7\n334\t\n335\t\fTable 1: DRC profiles used for generating datasets. Compressors and expanders\n336\tshare the same parameters except the threshold L.\n337\t\n338\tParameter\n339\tLc (dBFS)\n340\tLe (dBFS)\n341\tR (dBin :dBout )\n342\tτvatt (ms)\n343\tτvrel (ms)\n344\tτgatt (ms)\n345\tτgrel (ms)\n346\tp (1 or 2)\n347\t\n348\tDescription\n349\tThreshold (compressor)\n350\tThreshold (expander)\n351\tRatio\n352\tEnvelope attack\n353\tEnvelope release\n354\tGain attack\n355\tGain release\n356\tDetector type\n357\t\n358\tParam. Range\n359\t[-60,-20]\n360\t[-20, -8]\n361\t[2, 15]\n362\t5, 130\n363\t[10, 500]\n364\t[25, 2,000]\n365\t2\n366\t\n367\tTable 2: Top-10 features ranked by matched success rate. A higher score indicates that the recovered signal is more often closer to the reference than its\n368\tmatched processed counterpart.\n369\tCompression\n370\tFeature DH1\n371\tSR(%)\n372\t91.2\n373\tExpansion\n374\tFeature DH1\n375\tSR(%)\n376\t80.0\n377\t\n378\tDH4\n379\t91.2\n380\t\n381\tDH5\n382\t90.3\n383\t\n384\tDCOff ratio\n385\t86.5\n386\t\n387\tDH3\n388\t83.7\n389\t\n390\tDCOff\n391\t79.7\n392\t\n393\tBW\n394\t78.3\n395\t\n396\tDH7\n397\t70.4\n398\t\n399\tAVSP4\n400\t70.4\n401\t\n402\tAVSP2\n403\t66.0\n404\t\n405\tDH4\n406\t80.0\n407\t\n408\tDH5\n409\t78.4\n410\t\n411\tDH2\n412\t71.6\n413\t\n414\tDH6\n415\t67.9\n416\t\n417\tAVSP5\n418\t67.2\n419\t\n420\tAVSP3\n421\t64.9\n422\t\n423\tAVSP4\n424\t61.7\n425\t\n426\tBW\n427\t57.7\n428\t\n429\tDCOff\n430\t54.5\n431\t\n432\t(a) Compression\n433\t\n434\t(b) Expansion\n435\t\n436\tFigure 2: Projection of the original, processed, and recovered signals in the\n437\tselected feature space using the top-3 matched success-rate features.\n438\ttrajectory. For expansion, the same trend is observed, but with a larger spread\n439\tof the deexpanded signals, which indicates a more difficult inversion problem.\n440\tThe quantitative results are consistent with these visual observations. In the\n441\tselected feature space, the average distance between the original and processed\n442\t8\n443\t\n444\t\fsignals is 2.62 for compression and 1.08 for expansion, whereas the average distance between the original and recovered signals is reduced to 1.30 and 0.68,\n445\trespectively. The corresponding matched success rates are 90.8% for compression and 80.0% for expansion. These results support the relevance of the selected\n446\tfeature space for the inversion task and confirm that expansion remains more\n447\tchallenging than compression.\n448\t\n449\t5.3\n450\t\n451\tBlack-box DRC inversion\n452\t\n453\t5.3.1\n454\t\n455\tDry Signal Reference Point\n456\t\n457\tSince the original dry signal x is not available at inference time, the inversion is\n458\tguided by a reference point denoted ϕref that is defined in the selected feature\n459\tspace. Because compression and expansion are treated as two distinct inversion\n460\tproblems, two separate reference points are computed.\n461\tFor each task (compression or expansion), ϕ(·) denotes the corresponding\n462\tselected feature vector restricted to the top-ranked feature subset. All feature\n463\tvectors are first standardized by z-score normalization. The dry reference point\n464\tϕref is then defined as the centroid of the standardized dry feature vectors of\n465\tthe considered dataset.\n466\tThis reference point provides a compact representation of the dry-signal region in the selected feature space and serves as the target of the black-box\n467\toptimization. In practice, using effect-specific normalization and effect-specific\n468\tdry centroids is important, since compression and expansion induce different geometric distributions in the feature space. In the selected three-dimensional feature space, the resulting dry reference coordinates are ϕcomp\n469\t= [1.11, 1.11, 1.11]\n470\tref\n471\tand ϕexp\n472\t=\n473\t[0.50,\n474\t0.50,\n475\t0.47].\n476\tref\n477\tIn our experiments, the feature normalization statistics and the dry reference\n478\tpoint were computed exclusively from the training set and kept fixed during all\n479\ttest-time experiments.\n480\t5.3.2\n481\t\n482\tResults and visualization\n483\t\n484\tWe compare two gradient-free black-box optimization algorithms for blind DRC\n485\tinversion: Pattern Search [21], with at most 80 iterations and 300 function evaluations, and Bayesian Optimization [22], initialized with 12 initial evaluations\n486\tand a total budget of 80 objective evaluations.\n487\tIn both cases, optimization is performed in a normalized six-dimensional\n488\tDRC parameter space (cf. Table 1 with p fixed to 2) and aims to minimize the\n489\tEuclidean distance to the dry reference point in the selected feature space. For\n490\tBayesian Optimization, we also evaluate a variant initialized with the Music\n491\tEffect Encoder (MEE) estimate and regularized by the corresponding prior,\n492\tdenoted as Bayesian + MEE (µ = 0.2).\n493\tTwo additional baselines are considered: CleanUMamba [24] that is used\n494\tas an end-to-end waveform baseline, and Music Effect Encoder (MEE) [2, 25]\n495\tthat is used both as a parameter-estimation baseline and as a prior for initialization. In the direct Music Effect Encoder (MEE) setting, the Music Effect\n496\t9\n497\t\n498\t\f(a) Comp, Pattern Search\n499\t\n500\t(b) Comp, Bayesian\n501\t\n502\t(c) Exp, Pattern Search\n503\t\n504\t(d) Exp, Bayesian\n505\t\n506\tFigure 3: Recovered signals projected in the selected feature space for the compression and expansion inversion tasks, in comparison with the baseline methods.\n507\tEncoder (MEE)-predicted parameters are directly used for inverse Dynamic\n508\tRange Control (DRC) without subsequent optimization. Both baseline models\n509\tare pretrained on the MedleyDB dataset, which is preprocessed using the 30\n510\tcompression and expansion profiles listed in Table 1.\n511\tFigure 3 displays the recovered signals in the selected feature space for the\n512\tdifferent optimization strategies. In all cases, the recovered signals form a cluster around the original dry signals, which confirms that the selected feature\n513\tspace remains informative for blind inversion. For compression, Pattern Search\n514\tproduces the closest recovered cloud to the original cluster, while Bayesian Optimization exhibits a slightly larger spread. For expansion, the Bayesian + Music\n515\tEffect Encoder (MEE) setting yields the tightest cluster around the dry reference, indicating that the Music Effect Encoder (MEE) prior is relevant for this\n516\tmore difficult inversion task. Table 3 reports quantitative results in terms of\n517\tfeature-space distance to ϕref and parameter estimation mean squared error.\n518\tOverall, the proposed optimization-based methods significantly outperform the\n519\tbaseline. For compression, Pattern Search achieves the best reconstruction qual10\n520\t\n521\t\fTable 3: Averaged comparative results in terms of feature-space distance to ϕref\n522\tand parameter estimation MSE.\n523\tCompression\n524\tApproach\n525\tPattern Search\n526\tBayesian\n527\tBayesian + MEE\n528\tMEE [4]\n529\tCleanUMamba [24]\n530\t\n531\tExpansion\n532\t\n533\td(ϕ(x), ϕ(x̂)) ↓\n534\t\n535\tMSE(θ, θ̂) ↓\n536\t\n537\td(ϕ(x), ϕ(x̂)) ↓\n538\t\n539\tMSE(θ, θ̂) ↓\n540\t\n541\t0.29\n542\t0.41\n543\t0.39\n544\t0.90\n545\t2.31\n546\t\n547\t0.36\n548\t0.23\n549\t0.19\n550\t0.05\n551\t–\n552\t\n553\t0.29\n554\t0.28\n555\t0.25\n556\t0.77\n557\t0.91\n558\t\n559\t0.21\n560\t0.17\n561\t0.15\n562\t0.19\n563\t–\n564\t\n565\tity in the selected feature space, whereas for expansion, Bayesian Optimization\n566\tyields the best overall performance.\n567\tHowever, the performance gap between the two methods remains moderate,\n568\twhile their computational costs differ substantially.\n569\tExperiments were conducted on an Intel Xeon W-2133 CPU @ 3.60 GHz.\n570\tOn average, Pattern Search requires 431 s and 530 s per 30-second excerpt for\n571\tcompression and expansion, respectively, whereas Bayesian Optimization requires only 124 s and 187 s. Despite slightly lower performance in some cases,\n572\tBayesian Optimization provides a more favorable trade-off between reconstruction quality and computational efficiency, making it the preferred method in our\n573\tsetting.\n574\tFigure 4 reports a broader distributional analysis with respect to two reference methods, using Mean Squared Error (LMSE ), Mel loss (LMel ), ScaleInvariant Signal-to-Distortion Ratio (SI-SDR), and the perceptual 2f-score [26],\n575\tas proposed in [4]. First, a model-based DRC inversion is performed using the\n576\tground-truth parameters θ as a reference, denoted as “Ref”. The results in this\n577\tcase represent the upper bound on performance.\n578\tWe also include a naive model-based inversion baseline, referred to as “anchor”, that uses fixed average parameter values from the 30 profiles:\n579\tCompressor:\n580\tθ̄ = {−40.5, 8.7, 68.7, 68.5, 252.4, 1031.3}\n581\tExpander:\n582\tθ̄ = {−14.0, 8.6, 68.5, 68.7, 253.4, 1043.6}\n583\tWe invert the processed signal y in the test sets using these profiles and\n584\tcompare the reconstructed signals with the ground truth x. This baseline reflects\n585\tthe expected performance without learned parameter estimation and quantifies\n586\tthe benefit of the proposed learning-based approach.\n587\tThe box plots show that the proposed feature-guided inversion methods\n588\tconsistently outperform both the anchor and CleanUMamba baselines for both\n589\tcompression and expansion. The gap is particularly clear for compression, while\n590\t11\n591\t\n592\t\fRef 1e-05\n593\tAnchor\n594\tPattern\n595\tBayes\n596\tBayes+MEE\n597\tMEE\n598\tCleanUMamba\n599\t0\n600\t\n601\t0.012\n602\t\n603\t45\n604\t\n605\t0.035\n606\t\n607\t3\n608\t\n609\t0.0025\n610\t\n611\t0.32\n612\t0.46\n613\t\n614\t0.004\n615\t\n616\t0.43\n617\t\n618\t10 3\n619\t\n620\tMSE\n621\tx, x\n622\t\n623\t10 2\n624\t\n625\t10 1\n626\t\n627\tMel\n628\tx, x\n629\t\n630\t43\n631\t\n632\t7.9\n633\t2.2\n634\t\n635\t100 0\n636\t\n637\t40\n638\t\n639\t13\n640\t\n641\t0.85\n642\t\n643\t10 1\n644\t\n645\t10 2\n646\t\n647\t49\n648\t\n649\t13\n650\t\n651\t0.023\n652\t\n653\t10 4\n654\t\n655\t16\n656\t\n657\t15\n658\t\n659\t0.0043\n660\t\n661\t0.0081\n662\t\n663\t90\n664\t\n665\t13\n666\t\n667\t100\n668\t\n669\t37\n670\t\n671\t11\n672\t\n673\t0\n674\t\n675\t17\n676\t\n677\t10\n678\t\n679\t20\n680\t\n681\tSISDR\n682\t\n683\t30\n684\t\n685\t40\n686\t\n687\t50 0\n688\t\n689\t20\n690\t\n691\t40\n692\t\n693\t60\n694\t\n695\t2f-score\n696\t\n697\t80\n698\t\n699\t100\n700\t\n701\t(a) Compression inversion task.\n702\tRef\n703\tAnchor\n704\tPattern\n705\tBayes\n706\tBayes+MEE\n707\tMEE\n708\tCleanUMamba\n709\t\n710\t1.2e-05\n711\t\n712\t0.012\n713\t\n714\t45\n715\t\n716\t0.07\n717\t\n718\t0.45\n719\t\n720\t0.0018\n721\t\n722\t6\n723\t\n724\t0.35\n725\t\n726\t0.0059\n727\t\n728\t13\n729\t\n730\t0.49\n731\t\n732\t0.0054\n733\t\n734\t0.58\n735\t\n736\t0.0069\n737\t\n738\t0.5\n739\t\n740\t0.0054\n741\t\n742\tMSE\n743\tx, x\n744\t\n745\t10 2\n746\t\n747\t10 1\n748\t\n749\tMel\n750\tx, x\n751\t\n752\t45\n753\t16\n754\t\n755\t44\n756\t\n757\t17\n758\t\n759\t45\n760\t\n761\t14\n762\t1.6\n763\t\n764\t100 6 10 5 10 4 10 3 10 2 10 1 100 0\n765\t\n766\t83\n767\t7\n768\t\n769\t100\n770\t\n771\t42\n772\t\n773\t9.2\n774\t\n775\t10\n776\t\n777\t0\n778\t\n779\t10\n780\t\n781\t25\n782\t\n783\t20\n784\t\n785\tSISDR\n786\t\n787\t30\n788\t\n789\t40\n790\t\n791\t50 0\n792\t\n793\t20\n794\t\n795\t40\n796\t\n797\t60\n798\t\n799\t2f-score\n800\t\n801\t80\n802\t\n803\t100\n804\t\n805\t(b) Expansion inversion task.\n806\t\n807\tFigure 4: Box plot comparison of the proposed method and baseline methods for\n808\tDRC inversion. The figure contains two subfigures corresponding to the compression\n809\t(a) and expansion (b) inversion tasks, respectively. Each subfigure is organized with\n810\terror metrics as columns. Each box plot shows the distribution of performance across\n811\tall test chunks, including the minimum, first quartile, median, third quartile, and\n812\tmaximum values. The mean value is indicated next to each box.\n813\t\n814\tthe expansion task remains more challenging and shows broader dispersion of\n815\tresults.\n816\t\n817\t6\n818\t\n819\tAblation Study\n820\t\n821\tTo evaluate the contribution of the MEE prior, we compare the black-box optimization with and without MEE-based initialization. In both cases, the same\n822\tfeature space, inverse DRC model, and optimization procedure are used; the\n823\tonly difference is whether the parameter search is initialized from the MEE\n824\tprediction or from a random initialization.\n825\tMoreover, we report the direct MEE inversion as a reference, obtained by\n826\tapplying the inverse DRC model with the MEE estimated parameters without\n827\tfurther optimization. Figure 5 provides a qualitative comparison in the selected\n828\tfeature space. Combining the global quantitative results reported in Table 3,\n829\tBayesian optimization benefits from MEE initialization, reducing the parameter\n830\terror and slightly improving the feature-space distance for both tasks. This\n831\ttrend is also visible in the displayed feature space projections. In Figure 4, the\n832\trecovered signal generated by the proposed Bayes+MEE inversion method is\n833\tcloser to the dry reference signal than the other methods. Although the pattern\n834\tsearch method yields better results, considering the time cost, we believe the\n835\tBayes+MEE method is the better choice.\n836\tAn important point is that using only the MEE model for DRC parameter\n837\t\n838\t12\n839\t\n840\t\f(a) Compression\n841\t\n842\t(b) Expansion\n843\t\n844\tFigure 5: Comparison of signal projections in the selected feature space, with and\n845\twithout MEE initialization, using the Bayesian approach.\n846\t\n847\testimation achieves a lower MSE error than Bayes+MEE for compression, while\n848\tproducing a much worse recovered signal in feature space. The black-box optimization does not minimize the parameter error directly; instead, it minimizes\n849\tthe feature-space distance between the recovered signal and the dry reference.\n850\tAs a result, the optimization may move away from the MEE parameter estimate\n851\tif another parameter configuration yields a recovered signal that is closer to the\n852\tdry reference in the selected feature space.\n853\tThis observation supports the proposed two-stage strategy where the MEE\n854\toutput provides a meaningful initialization, while the subsequent black-box optimization refines this estimate with respect to the feature-space objective. Overall, the ablation study shows that MEE initialization is relevant and complementary to the proposed optimization framework.\n855\t\n856\t7\n857\t\n858\tConclusion and Future Work\n859\t\n860\tWe introduced a black-box optimization framework for estimating the parameters of an inverse dynamic range compression model using a feature-based\n861\tobjective. To the best of our knowledge, this work is among the first to explore\n862\tblack-box optimization for DRC parameter estimation in a perceptual feature\n863\tspace. Our results highlight the potential of black-box optimization for leveraging non-differentiable, interpretable, and perceptually motivated features in\n864\taudio tasks, paving the way for feature-driven optimization approaches in audio\n865\tprocessing. Future work will investigate more advanced feature representations,\n866\tincluding learned perceptual embeddings, as well as more efficient optimization\n867\tstrategies to reduce computational cost.\n868\t\n869\t13\n870\t\n871\t\fReferences\n872\t[1] J. D. Reiss and A. McPherson, Audio Effects. CRC Press, 2014.\n873\t[2] C. Peladeau and G. Peeters, “Blind estimation of audio effects using an autoencoder approach and differentiable digital signal processing,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n874\t2024, pp. 856–860.\n875\t[3] C. Peladeau, D. Fourer, and G. Peeters, “Audio processor parameters: estimating\n876\tdistributions instead of deterministic values,” in Proc. International Conference\n877\ton Digital Audio Effects (DAFx25), 2025.\n878\t[4] H. Sun, D. Fourer, and H. Maaref, “Neural-enhanced dynamic range compression inversion: A hybrid approach for restoring audio dynamics,” arXiv preprint\n879\tarXiv:2411.04337, 2024.\n880\t[5] S. Nercessian, “Neural parametric equalizer matching using differentiable biquads,” in Proc. International Conference on Digital Audio Effects (DAFx20),\n881\t2020.\n882\t[6] J. T. Colonel, C. J. Steinmetz, M. Michelen, and J. D. Reiss, “Direct design of\n883\tbiquad filter cascades with deep learning by sampling random polynomials,” in\n884\tProc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n885\t(ICASSP), 2022.\n886\t[7] C. J. Steinmetz, N. J. Bryan, and J. D. Reiss, “Style transfer of audio effects with\n887\tdifferentiable signal processing,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2207.08759, 2022.\n888\t[8] S. Alarie, C. Audet, A. E. Gheribi, M. Kokkolaras, and S. Le Digabel, “Two\n889\tdecades of blackbox optimization applications,” EURO Journal on Computational\n890\tOptimization, vol. 9, p. 100011, 2021.\n891\t[9] U. Zölzer, DAFX: Digital Audio Effects. Chichester, UK: Wiley Online Library,\n892\t2011.\n893\t[10] D. Giannoulis, M. Massberg, and J. D. Reiss, “Digital dynamic range compressor design—a tutorial and analysis,” Journal of the Audio Engineering Society,\n894\tvol. 60, no. 6, pp. 399–408, 2012.\n895\t[11] S. Gorlow and J. D. Reiss, “Model-based inversion of dynamic range compression,”\n896\tIEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 21, no. 7,\n897\tpp. 1434–1444, 2013.\n898\t[12] S. H. Hawley, B. Colburn, and S. I. Mimilakis, “Signaltrain: Profiling audio compressors with deep neural networks,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1905.11928, 2019.\n899\t[13] A. Wright, E.-P. Damskägg, and V. Välimäki, “Real-time black-box modelling\n900\twith recurrent neural networks,” in Proc. International Conference on Digital\n901\tAudio Effects (DAFx19). University of Birmingham, 2019.\n902\t[14] D. Sheng and G. Fazekas, “A feature learning siamese model for intelligent control\n903\tof the dynamic range compressor,” in 2019 International Joint Conference on\n904\tNeural Networks (IJCNN), 2019, pp. 1–8.\n905\t[15] J. Engel, L. Hantrakul, C. Gu, and A. Roberts, “Ddsp: Differentiable digital\n906\tsignal processing,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2001.04643, 2020.\n907\t[16] O. Take, K. Watanabe, T. Nakatsuka, T. Cheng, T. Nakano, M. Goto,\n908\tS. Takamichi, and H. Saruwatari, “Audio effect chain estimation and dry signal recovery from multi-effect-processed musical signals,” in Proc. International\n909\tConference on Digital Audio Effects (DAFx24), 2024, pp. 1–8.\n910\t\n911\t14\n912\t\n913\t\f[17] M. Comunità, C. J. Steinmetz, and J. D. Reiss, “Differentiable black-box and graybox modeling of nonlinear audio effects,” Frontiers in Signal Processing, vol. 5,\n914\tp. 1580395, 2025.\n915\t[18] M. A. M. Ramírez, O. Wang, P. Smaragdis, and N. J. Bryan, “Differentiable signal\n916\tprocessing with black-box audio effects,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference\n917\ton Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2021, pp. 66–70.\n918\t[19] Y. Gong, Y.-A. Chung, and J. Glass, “AST: Audio Spectrogram Transformer,” in\n919\tProc. Interspeech 2021, 2021, pp. 571–575.\n920\t[20] D. Fourer and G. Peeters, “Objective characterization of audio signal quality:\n921\tapplications to music collection description,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2017, pp. 711–715.\n922\t[21] N. V. Findler, C. Lo, and R. Lo, “Pattern search for optimization,” Mathematics\n923\tand computers in simulation, vol. 29, no. 1, pp. 41–50, 1987.\n924\t[22] M. A. Gelbart, J. Snoek, and R. P. Adams, “Bayesian optimization with unknown\n925\tconstraints,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1403.5607, 2014.\n926\t[23] R. M. Bittner, J. Salamon, M. Tierney, M. Mauch, C. Cannam, and J. P. Bello,\n927\t“Medleydb: A multitrack dataset for annotation-intensive mir research.” in Proc.\n928\tInternational Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR), 2014,\n929\tpp. 155–160.\n930\t[24] S. Groot, Q. Chen, J. C. Van Gemert, and C. Gao, “Cleanumamba: a compact\n931\tmamba network for speech denoising using channel pruning,” in Proc. IEEE ISCAS, 2025, pp. 1–5.\n932\t[25] J. Koo, S. Paik, and K. Lee, “End-to-end music remastering system using selfsupervised and adversarial training,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on\n933\tAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2022, pp. 4608–4612.\n934\t[26] T. Kastner and J. Herre, “An efficient model for estimating subjective quality of\n935\tseparated audio source signals,” in Proc. IEEE WASPAA, 2019, pp. 95–99.\n936\t\n937\t15\n938\t\n939\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "83a541b0-3f66-43ce-a363-20dd19ed248b", "uuid": "fef2d9bc-97e0-4344-aa27-92c55778dc36", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T06:17:38.659Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/drc_paper_2607.19645.txt", "content": "Black-Box Optimization for Identifying and\nInverting Audio Dynamic Range Control Effects\nHaoran Sun\nDominique Fourer\nHichem Maaref\nIBISC (EA 4526), Univ. Évry Paris-Saclay\n\narXiv:2607.19645v1 [cs.SD] 22 Jul 2026\n\nJuly 23, 2026\nAbstract\nDynamic Range Compression (DRC) is a widely used nonlinear audio\neffect whose parameters are often unknown, making blind estimation and\ninversion challenging. In this work, we formulate DRC parameter estimation as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptually motivated\nfeature space. Given an observed signal and a reference representation, we\nestimate the parameters that minimize the distance between feature descriptors of the reconstructed and reference signals. Unlike gradient-based\napproaches, the proposed method does not require differentiability of the\nDRC model or the feature extraction pipeline, enabling the use of nonlinear and histogram-based descriptors. Experimental results demonstrate\nthat the proposed method achieves competitive performance in blind parameter estimation and dry signal recovery, outperforming or matching\nstate-of-the-art models in terms of reconstruction quality.\n\n1\n\nIntroduction\n\nThe estimation of audio processor parameters from observed signals is an important topic in audio signal processing, with applications ranging from audio\nrestoration and remixing to effect modeling and analysis [1]. In particular,\nthe inversion of Dynamic Range Control (DRC) remains a challenging problem\ndue to its highly nonlinear, time-dependent, and often non-invertible nature.\nThese properties make the recovery of both the original signal and the underlying compression parameters inherently ambiguous, especially in blind settings\nwhere only the processed signal is available.\nRecent works have explored data-driven approaches for audio effect parameter estimation. For instance, [2] proposes an autoencoder framework combined\nwith differentiable digital signal processing (DDSP) modules to estimate effect\nparameters in an end-to-end manner. Extending this paradigm, [3] introduces\n\n1\n\n\fprobabilistic models that capture parameter uncertainty by predicting distributions instead of point estimates. Similarly, hybrid approaches combining deep\nlearning and signal processing have been proposed for DRC inversion [4].\nIn such approaches, the use of differentiable signal processing blocks allows gradient-based optimization of audio parameters. This approach has been\nsuccessfully applied to various audio effects, including equalization and style\ntransfer [5–7]. More generally, differentiable formulations of signal processing\noperators have enabled efficient parameter estimation within end-to-end learning frameworks.\nHowever, these approaches rely on the differentiability of both the signal\nprocessing chain and the objective function. In practice, this assumption may\nnot hold when the evaluation is performed in perceptually motivated feature\nspaces, which often involve nonlinear and non-differentiable operations such\nas histogram-based descriptors or handcrafted audio features. In such cases,\ngradient-based optimization becomes inapplicable or unreliable.\nIn this work, we propose to formulate the estimation of DRC parameters\nas a black-box optimization problem [8]. The objective function is defined as a\ndistance in a feature space between a reference representation and the output\nof a parametric inverse DRC model. This formulation does not require differentiability and enables the use of derivative-free optimization methods. The main\ncontributions of this work are as follows:\n• We propose a novel formulation of blind DRC parameter estimation and\neffect inversion as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptual feature\nspace.\n• We identify a perceptually motivated feature space suitable for capturing the effects of dynamic range. In particular, we show that dynamic\nhistogram descriptors can provide an effective optimization space.\n• We propose a derivative-free optimization approach that can estimate perceptually plausible parameters without requiring differentiable models.\n\n2\n\nRelated Work\n\nModel-based inversion: Blind estimation of audio effect parameters has been\naddressed using model-based, data-driven, and hybrid approaches. Classical\ndigital audio effects and their analytical formulations are detailed in [9, 10].\nEarly inversion methods exploit explicit knowledge of the processor equations\nto recover the original signal or estimate effect parameters. For example, Gorlow\nand Reiss [11] proposed a model-based inversion framework for dynamic range\ncompression assuming complete knowledge of the compressor structure. While\nphysically interpretable, such approaches are limited to scenarios where the\nprocessing model is fully specified.\nNeural effect parameter estimation and modeling: Recent work\nmainly uses deep learning to model audio effects and to estimate their parameters. SignalTrain [12] and the recurrent architecture proposed by Wright\n2\n\n\fet al. [13] focused on black-box emulation of nonlinear audio processors from\ninput-output examples, whereas Sheng and Fazekas [14] addressed the related\ntask of compressor parameter estimation using a siamese feature-learning architecture. They showed that neural networks can accurately emulate nonlinear\naudio processors from input–output examples without requiring explicit knowledge of their internal structure. More recently, supervised neural approaches\nhave been proposed for blind audio effect parameter estimation [2, 4], while\nprobabilistic formulations have been investigated to model ambiguities inherent\nto inverse problems [3].\nDifferentiable Digital Signal Processing: In parallel, Differentiable Digital Signal Processing (DDSP) enables the integration of signal processing algorithms into end-to-end trainable neural networks [15]. This paradigm has\nbeen extended to differentiable audio effect modeling, virtual analog systems,\nand audio style transfer [5–7, 16, 17]. In particular, Ramírez et al. [18] proposed DeepAFx, which combines differentiable DSP with simultaneous perturbation stochastic approximation (SPSA) to optimize the parameters of nondifferentiable audio effects. While these methods exploit differentiable processing chains or gradient approximations, they generally assume optimization in\nthe signal domain or a differentiable objective function.\nPositioning of our work: Our work differs from previous approaches in\ntwo important aspects. First, rather than learning a forward model of the\ncompressor or directly regressing its parameters, we formulate blind compressor\nparameter estimation as a derivative-free optimization problem in a perceptually\nmotivated feature space.\nSecond, instead of relying on differentiable signal processing and gradientbased optimization, the objective function is evaluated in a feature space containing non-differentiable dynamic histogram descriptors. This makes gradientbased optimization inapplicable and motivates the use of black-box optimization. By combining a model-based inverse compressor with derivative-free optimization, our framework bridges model-based inversion and learning-based\nparameter estimation.\n\n3\n\nProblem Formulation\n\n3.1\n\nOverview\n\nWe consider the blind estimation of dynamic range compressor (DRC) parameters from an observed signal:\ny = DRC(x, θ),\n\n(1)\n\nwhere x denotes the unknown dry signal and θ the unknown DRC parameter\nvector. Since neither the original signal nor the compressor parameters are\navailable, recovering θ from y is an ill-posed inverse problem, as multiple combinations of dry signals and compressor parameters may produce perceptually\nsimilar observations.\n3\n\n\f,\n\nEnvelope\nDetection\n\nStatic Curve\nComputation\n\n,\n\n,\n\nGain Filter\nSmoothing\n\n,\n\nFigure 1: Illustration of a dynamic range controller.\nRather than jointly estimating the dry signal x and the DRC parameters θ,\nwe exploit the availability of a model-based DRC inversion operator [11]. Given\na candidate parameter vector θ, the inverse model produces a reconstructed dry\nsignal:\nx̂(θ) = DRC−1 (y, θ).\n\n(2)\n\nThe quality of this reconstruction is assessed in a perceptually motivated\nfeature space. Let ϕ(·) denote a perceptually motivated feature extractor and\nlet ϕref be a reference feature vector representing the expected characteristics\nof dry signals. Parameter estimation is formulated as the optimization problem:\n\u0001\u0001\nθ̂ = arg min ds ϕref , ϕ DRC−1 (y, θ) ,\n(3)\nθ∈Θ\n\nwhere ds (·, ·) denotes a distance in the feature space.\nOnce the parameters have been estimated, the recovered dry signal is obtained as\nx̂(θ̂) = DRC−1 (y, θ̂).\n\n3.2\n\n(4)\n\nDynamic Range Control\n\nDynamic Range Control (DRC) reduces the dynamic range of a signal by attenuating high-amplitude components while leaving low-level components mostly\nunchanged (compression); or increases the dynamic range by attenuating lowamplitude components while leaving high-level components mostly unchanged\n(expansion) [10]. This results in a more controlled signal amplitude and is commonly used in music production, broadcasting, and audio mastering.\nFormally, DRC is a nonlinear, time-dependent transformation that modifies\nan input signal x[n] (assumed real-valued and discrete, with sampling frequency\nFs ) through a time-varying gain function g[n]:\ny[n] = DRC (x, θ) = x[n] gx,θ [n],\n\n4\n\n(5)\n\n\fwhere θ denotes the set of compressor parameters. A typical DRC model [9]\n(cf. Fig. 1) is parameterized by:\nθ = {L, R, τvatt , τvrel , τgatt , τgrel , p},\nwhere L is the threshold (in dB), R is the compression ratio, τvatt and τvrel are\nthe attack and release times for the envelope detector, τgatt and τgrel are the\nattack and release times for gain smoothing, and p defines the detection type\n(e.g., peak or RMS).\nThe computation of the gain g[n] is typically performed in three stages including the detection envelope, the computation of the static compression curve\nand the gain smoothing. The compressed (wet) signal is finally obtained using\nEq. (5).\n\n3.3\n\nBlind Parameter Estimation and DRC Inversion\n\nThe inversion of dynamic range compression aims to recover the original signal\nx that produced the observed compressed signal y. Blind configurations, where\nthe DRC parameters are unknown, are challenging, but can be addressed using\ndata-driven approaches. In particular, hybrid strategies combining deep neural\nnetworks with model-based inversion have been proposed [4]. These methods\ntypically rely on neural architectures, such as Audio Spectrogram Transformers\nor effect encoders [2, 19], to estimate DRC parameters, which are then used\nwithin a signal processing model for inversion. In this work, the model-based\ninversion is based on the model proposed in [11] and extended in [4]. This approach assumes that the inverse model is parameterized by θ, which is estimated\nfrom the observed signal in order to perform inversion (cf. Eq. (4)).\n\n4\n\nFeature Space and Black-Box Optimization\n\n4.1\n\nPerceptually motivated audio features\n\nOur work is based on the audio quality features 1 introduced in [20] to describe\nthe perceptual impact of audio processing chains. These features are effective\nfor tasks such as predicting the type of dynamic range compression and the\nproduction decade of audio mixtures, suggesting that they encode meaningful information related to compression artifacts and dynamic structure. This\nwork uses a subset of these features, with particular emphasis on the dynamic\nhistogram (DH), which captures the distribution of signal amplitudes and is\ndirectly influenced by dynamic range compression.\nThe proposed feature set combines complementary descriptors that capture\ndynamic, spectral, and perceptual properties of the signal. It includes energyrelated measures (RMS, peak, crest factor), spectral descriptors (centroid, bandwidth, and statistics of the average spectrum), and perceptual stereo features\n(e.g., spectral entropy, background noise level, inter-channel correlation).\n1 https://github.com/dfourer/AQFeatures/\n\n5\n\n\fIn addition, we use distribution-based descriptors derived from the dynamic\nhistogram (DH), which characterizes the amplitude distribution over time. From\nthis histogram, we extract eight summary statistics (mean, peak value, peak position, centroid, median, entropy, standard deviation, and skewness), labeled as\nDH1–DH8, which are particularly sensitive to the redistribution of signal levels\ninduced by compression. All descriptors are concatenated into a single feature\nvector. Since many of these features involve nonlinear and non-differentiable\noperations, this motivates the use of black-box optimization methods.\n\n4.2\n\nFeature Space Selection\n\nBecause no ground-truth optimization criterion is available for blind inversion,\nwe evaluate candidate feature spaces using a proxy criterion measuring whether\ninversion consistently moves signals closer to the dry reference. Hence, for assessing the relevance of a feature space for inversion, we introduce a success rate\n(SR) criterion that evaluates whether the reconstructed signal is closer to the\nreference signal than the corresponding processed signal.\nGiven a reference signal x, we generate processed signals y i = DRC(x, θi )\nand corresponding reconstructions x̂i = DRC−1 (y i , θi ). Hence, a feature space\nis considered effective if:\n\u0001\n\u0001\nd ϕ(x̂i ), ϕ(x) < d ϕ(y i ), ϕ(x) ,\n(6)\nwhere d denotes the Euclidean distance in the feature space.\nThe success rate is defined as\nSR =\n\nN\n\u0001\n\u0001\u0001\n1 X\n1 d ϕ(x̂i ), ϕ(x) < d ϕ(yi ), ϕ(x) ,\nN i=1\n\n(7)\n\nwhere N is the number of samples and 1(·) is the indicator function that returns\n1 if the condition holds and 0 otherwise. A higher success rate indicates that\nthe feature space better reflects reconstruction quality relative to the processed\nsignal.\n\n4.3\n\nBlack-box optimization\n\nThe problem of DRC parameter estimation from the observed signal y is formulated as a black-box optimization problem in a perceptually relevant feature space. Following Eq. (3), the estimated parameter vector θ̂ minimizes\nthe distance between the reconstructed signal and a reference representation\nϕref ≈ ϕ(x):\n\u0001\n\u0001\nθ̂ = arg min d ϕ DRC−1 (y; θ) , ϕref .\n(8)\nθ\n\nSince the objective function involves nonlinear and non-differentiable operations (e.g., feature extraction and statistical descriptors), gradient-based optimization methods are not applicable.\n\n6\n\n\fTo improve robustness, the optimization is performed in a normalized parameter space. The physical parameter bounds θmin and θmax are derived from\nthe admissible ranges of the considered processing model. A normalized parameter vector z ∈ [0, 1]6 is then mapped to the corresponding physical parameters\nθ.\nWe further incorporate a prior estimate θ̂0 , obtained using a data-driven\nDRC parameter estimator [4], by introducing a regularization term. The final\nobjective is defined as:\n\u0001\nL(θ; y) = d ϕ(DRC −1 (y, θ)), ϕref + µ θ − θ̂0\n\n.\n\n(9)\n\n2\n\nwhere ∥.∥2 denotes the ℓ2 -norm.\nIn this study, we consider two distinct black-box optimization methods: Pattern Search [21] and Bayesian Optimization [22]. After optimization, the estimated parameters θ̂ are used within the inverse DRC model to reconstruct the\nsignal x̂.\n\n5\n\nNumerical Results\n\n5.1\n\nDataset\n\nWe use audio material from the MedleyDB dataset [23].\nBased on the available metadata, we select dry mixture signals from five\nmusical genres: classical, rock, electronic, pop, and jazz. For each genre, five\n30-second excerpts are randomly sampled from distinct recordings, resulting in\na total of 25 original signals. All excerpts are converted to mono by averaging\nthe stereo channels.\nCompression, expansion, and the corresponding model-based inversion are\nperformed using the framework proposed in [4]. Each signal is processed using\n30 predefined DRC profiles, whose parameter ranges are detailed in Table 1.\nThis yields a total of 750 processed samples of 30 seconds for each task.\n\n5.2\n\nFeature space selection\n\nTable 2 presents the top-ranked features for compression and expansion. In both\ncases, the same three features from the dynamic histogram, DH1, DH4, and DH5,\nachieve the highest scores. We therefore select these three features to define the\nfinal feature space for the subsequent experiments.\nFigure 2 shows the projection of all five musical styles into the selected threedimensional feature space. Compression and expansion are displayed separately.\nIn both cases, the processed signals move away from the original references,\nwhile the recovered signals tend to remain closer to them. This observation\nis confirmed by the average distance to the original signal, denoted d¯ that is\nsmaller. This effect is more pronounced for compression, where the decompressed points nearly overlap with the original cluster along most of the main\n\n7\n\n\fTable 1: DRC profiles used for generating datasets. Compressors and expanders\nshare the same parameters except the threshold L.\n\nParameter\nLc (dBFS)\nLe (dBFS)\nR (dBin :dBout )\nτvatt (ms)\nτvrel (ms)\nτgatt (ms)\nτgrel (ms)\np (1 or 2)\n\nDescription\nThreshold (compressor)\nThreshold (expander)\nRatio\nEnvelope attack\nEnvelope release\nGain attack\nGain release\nDetector type\n\nParam. Range\n[-60,-20]\n[-20, -8]\n[2, 15]\n5, 130\n[10, 500]\n[25, 2,000]\n2\n\nTable 2: Top-10 features ranked by matched success rate. A higher score indicates that the recovered signal is more often closer to the reference than its\nmatched processed counterpart.\nCompression\nFeature DH1\nSR(%)\n91.2\nExpansion\nFeature DH1\nSR(%)\n80.0\n\nDH4\n91.2\n\nDH5\n90.3\n\nDCOff ratio\n86.5\n\nDH3\n83.7\n\nDCOff\n79.7\n\nBW\n78.3\n\nDH7\n70.4\n\nAVSP4\n70.4\n\nAVSP2\n66.0\n\nDH4\n80.0\n\nDH5\n78.4\n\nDH2\n71.6\n\nDH6\n67.9\n\nAVSP5\n67.2\n\nAVSP3\n64.9\n\nAVSP4\n61.7\n\nBW\n57.7\n\nDCOff\n54.5\n\n(a) Compression\n\n(b) Expansion\n\nFigure 2: Projection of the original, processed, and recovered signals in the\nselected feature space using the top-3 matched success-rate features.\ntrajectory. For expansion, the same trend is observed, but with a larger spread\nof the deexpanded signals, which indicates a more difficult inversion problem.\nThe quantitative results are consistent with these visual observations. In the\nselected feature space, the average distance between the original and processed\n8\n\n\fsignals is 2.62 for compression and 1.08 for expansion, whereas the average distance between the original and recovered signals is reduced to 1.30 and 0.68,\nrespectively. The corresponding matched success rates are 90.8% for compression and 80.0% for expansion. These results support the relevance of the selected\nfeature space for the inversion task and confirm that expansion remains more\nchallenging than compression.\n\n5.3\n\nBlack-box DRC inversion\n\n5.3.1\n\nDry Signal Reference Point\n\nSince the original dry signal x is not available at inference time, the inversion is\nguided by a reference point denoted ϕref that is defined in the selected feature\nspace. Because compression and expansion are treated as two distinct inversion\nproblems, two separate reference points are computed.\nFor each task (compression or expansion), ϕ(·) denotes the corresponding\nselected feature vector restricted to the top-ranked feature subset. All feature\nvectors are first standardized by z-score normalization. The dry reference point\nϕref is then defined as the centroid of the standardized dry feature vectors of\nthe considered dataset.\nThis reference point provides a compact representation of the dry-signal region in the selected feature space and serves as the target of the black-box\noptimization. In practice, using effect-specific normalization and effect-specific\ndry centroids is important, since compression and expansion induce different geometric distributions in the feature space. In the selected three-dimensional feature space, the resulting dry reference coordinates are ϕcomp\n= [1.11, 1.11, 1.11]\nref\nand ϕexp\n=\n[0.50,\n0.50,\n0.47].\nref\nIn our experiments, the feature normalization statistics and the dry reference\npoint were computed exclusively from the training set and kept fixed during all\ntest-time experiments.\n5.3.2\n\nResults and visualization\n\nWe compare two gradient-free black-box optimization algorithms for blind DRC\ninversion: Pattern Search [21], with at most 80 iterations and 300 function evaluations, and Bayesian Optimization [22], initialized with 12 initial evaluations\nand a total budget of 80 objective evaluations.\nIn both cases, optimization is performed in a normalized six-dimensional\nDRC parameter space (cf. Table 1 with p fixed to 2) and aims to minimize the\nEuclidean distance to the dry reference point in the selected feature space. For\nBayesian Optimization, we also evaluate a variant initialized with the Music\nEffect Encoder (MEE) estimate and regularized by the corresponding prior,\ndenoted as Bayesian + MEE (µ = 0.2).\nTwo additional baselines are considered: CleanUMamba [24] that is used\nas an end-to-end waveform baseline, and Music Effect Encoder (MEE) [2, 25]\nthat is used both as a parameter-estimation baseline and as a prior for initialization. In the direct Music Effect Encoder (MEE) setting, the Music Effect\n9\n\n\f(a) Comp, Pattern Search\n\n(b) Comp, Bayesian\n\n(c) Exp, Pattern Search\n\n(d) Exp, Bayesian\n\nFigure 3: Recovered signals projected in the selected feature space for the compression and expansion inversion tasks, in comparison with the baseline methods.\nEncoder (MEE)-predicted parameters are directly used for inverse Dynamic\nRange Control (DRC) without subsequent optimization. Both baseline models\nare pretrained on the MedleyDB dataset, which is preprocessed using the 30\ncompression and expansion profiles listed in Table 1.\nFigure 3 displays the recovered signals in the selected feature space for the\ndifferent optimization strategies. In all cases, the recovered signals form a cluster around the original dry signals, which confirms that the selected feature\nspace remains informative for blind inversion. For compression, Pattern Search\nproduces the closest recovered cloud to the original cluster, while Bayesian Optimization exhibits a slightly larger spread. For expansion, the Bayesian + Music\nEffect Encoder (MEE) setting yields the tightest cluster around the dry reference, indicating that the Music Effect Encoder (MEE) prior is relevant for this\nmore difficult inversion task. Table 3 reports quantitative results in terms of\nfeature-space distance to ϕref and parameter estimation mean squared error.\nOverall, the proposed optimization-based methods significantly outperform the\nbaseline. For compression, Pattern Search achieves the best reconstruction qual10\n\n\fTable 3: Averaged comparative results in terms of feature-space distance to ϕref\nand parameter estimation MSE.\nCompression\nApproach\nPattern Search\nBayesian\nBayesian + MEE\nMEE [4]\nCleanUMamba [24]\n\nExpansion\n\nd(ϕ(x), ϕ(x̂)) ↓\n\nMSE(θ, θ̂) ↓\n\nd(ϕ(x), ϕ(x̂)) ↓\n\nMSE(θ, θ̂) ↓\n\n0.29\n0.41\n0.39\n0.90\n2.31\n\n0.36\n0.23\n0.19\n0.05\n–\n\n0.29\n0.28\n0.25\n0.77\n0.91\n\n0.21\n0.17\n0.15\n0.19\n–\n\nity in the selected feature space, whereas for expansion, Bayesian Optimization\nyields the best overall performance.\nHowever, the performance gap between the two methods remains moderate,\nwhile their computational costs differ substantially.\nExperiments were conducted on an Intel Xeon W-2133 CPU @ 3.60 GHz.\nOn average, Pattern Search requires 431 s and 530 s per 30-second excerpt for\ncompression and expansion, respectively, whereas Bayesian Optimization requires only 124 s and 187 s. Despite slightly lower performance in some cases,\nBayesian Optimization provides a more favorable trade-off between reconstruction quality and computational efficiency, making it the preferred method in our\nsetting.\nFigure 4 reports a broader distributional analysis with respect to two reference methods, using Mean Squared Error (LMSE ), Mel loss (LMel ), ScaleInvariant Signal-to-Distortion Ratio (SI-SDR), and the perceptual 2f-score [26],\nas proposed in [4]. First, a model-based DRC inversion is performed using the\nground-truth parameters θ as a reference, denoted as “Ref”. The results in this\ncase represent the upper bound on performance.\nWe also include a naive model-based inversion baseline, referred to as “anchor”, that uses fixed average parameter values from the 30 profiles:\nCompressor:\nθ̄ = {−40.5, 8.7, 68.7, 68.5, 252.4, 1031.3}\nExpander:\nθ̄ = {−14.0, 8.6, 68.5, 68.7, 253.4, 1043.6}\nWe invert the processed signal y in the test sets using these profiles and\ncompare the reconstructed signals with the ground truth x. This baseline reflects\nthe expected performance without learned parameter estimation and quantifies\nthe benefit of the proposed learning-based approach.\nThe box plots show that the proposed feature-guided inversion methods\nconsistently outperform both the anchor and CleanUMamba baselines for both\ncompression and expansion. The gap is particularly clear for compression, while\n11\n\n\fRef 1e-05\nAnchor\nPattern\nBayes\nBayes+MEE\nMEE\nCleanUMamba\n0\n\n0.012\n\n45\n\n0.035\n\n3\n\n0.0025\n\n0.32\n0.46\n\n0.004\n\n0.43\n\n10 3\n\nMSE\nx, x\n\n10 2\n\n10 1\n\nMel\nx, x\n\n43\n\n7.9\n2.2\n\n100 0\n\n40\n\n13\n\n0.85\n\n10 1\n\n10 2\n\n49\n\n13\n\n0.023\n\n10 4\n\n16\n\n15\n\n0.0043\n\n0.0081\n\n90\n\n13\n\n100\n\n37\n\n11\n\n0\n\n17\n\n10\n\n20\n\nSISDR\n\n30\n\n40\n\n50 0\n\n20\n\n40\n\n60\n\n2f-score\n\n80\n\n100\n\n(a) Compression inversion task.\nRef\nAnchor\nPattern\nBayes\nBayes+MEE\nMEE\nCleanUMamba\n\n1.2e-05\n\n0.012\n\n45\n\n0.07\n\n0.45\n\n0.0018\n\n6\n\n0.35\n\n0.0059\n\n13\n\n0.49\n\n0.0054\n\n0.58\n\n0.0069\n\n0.5\n\n0.0054\n\nMSE\nx, x\n\n10 2\n\n10 1\n\nMel\nx, x\n\n45\n16\n\n44\n\n17\n\n45\n\n14\n1.6\n\n100 6 10 5 10 4 10 3 10 2 10 1 100 0\n\n83\n7\n\n100\n\n42\n\n9.2\n\n10\n\n0\n\n10\n\n25\n\n20\n\nSISDR\n\n30\n\n40\n\n50 0\n\n20\n\n40\n\n60\n\n2f-score\n\n80\n\n100\n\n(b) Expansion inversion task.\n\nFigure 4: Box plot comparison of the proposed method and baseline methods for\nDRC inversion. The figure contains two subfigures corresponding to the compression\n(a) and expansion (b) inversion tasks, respectively. Each subfigure is organized with\nerror metrics as columns. Each box plot shows the distribution of performance across\nall test chunks, including the minimum, first quartile, median, third quartile, and\nmaximum values. The mean value is indicated next to each box.\n\nthe expansion task remains more challenging and shows broader dispersion of\nresults.\n\n6\n\nAblation Study\n\nTo evaluate the contribution of the MEE prior, we compare the black-box optimization with and without MEE-based initialization. In both cases, the same\nfeature space, inverse DRC model, and optimization procedure are used; the\nonly difference is whether the parameter search is initialized from the MEE\nprediction or from a random initialization.\nMoreover, we report the direct MEE inversion as a reference, obtained by\napplying the inverse DRC model with the MEE estimated parameters without\nfurther optimization. Figure 5 provides a qualitative comparison in the selected\nfeature space. Combining the global quantitative results reported in Table 3,\nBayesian optimization benefits from MEE initialization, reducing the parameter\nerror and slightly improving the feature-space distance for both tasks. This\ntrend is also visible in the displayed feature space projections. In Figure 4, the\nrecovered signal generated by the proposed Bayes+MEE inversion method is\ncloser to the dry reference signal than the other methods. Although the pattern\nsearch method yields better results, considering the time cost, we believe the\nBayes+MEE method is the better choice.\nAn important point is that using only the MEE model for DRC parameter\n\n12\n\n\f(a) Compression\n\n(b) Expansion\n\nFigure 5: Comparison of signal projections in the selected feature space, with and\nwithout MEE initialization, using the Bayesian approach.\n\nestimation achieves a lower MSE error than Bayes+MEE for compression, while\nproducing a much worse recovered signal in feature space. The black-box optimization does not minimize the parameter error directly; instead, it minimizes\nthe feature-space distance between the recovered signal and the dry reference.\nAs a result, the optimization may move away from the MEE parameter estimate\nif another parameter configuration yields a recovered signal that is closer to the\ndry reference in the selected feature space.\nThis observation supports the proposed two-stage strategy where the MEE\noutput provides a meaningful initialization, while the subsequent black-box optimization refines this estimate with respect to the feature-space objective. Overall, the ablation study shows that MEE initialization is relevant and complementary to the proposed optimization framework.\n\n7\n\nConclusion and Future Work\n\nWe introduced a black-box optimization framework for estimating the parameters of an inverse dynamic range compression model using a feature-based\nobjective. To the best of our knowledge, this work is among the first to explore\nblack-box optimization for DRC parameter estimation in a perceptual feature\nspace. Our results highlight the potential of black-box optimization for leveraging non-differentiable, interpretable, and perceptually motivated features in\naudio tasks, paving the way for feature-driven optimization approaches in audio\nprocessing. Future work will investigate more advanced feature representations,\nincluding learned perceptual embeddings, as well as more efficient optimization\nstrategies to reduce computational cost.\n\n13\n\n\fReferences\n[1] J. D. Reiss and A. McPherson, Audio Effects. CRC Press, 2014.\n[2] C. Peladeau and G. Peeters, “Blind estimation of audio effects using an autoencoder approach and differentiable digital signal processing,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP),\n2024, pp. 856–860.\n[3] C. Peladeau, D. Fourer, and G. Peeters, “Audio processor parameters: estimating\ndistributions instead of deterministic values,” in Proc. International Conference\non Digital Audio Effects (DAFx25), 2025.\n[4] H. Sun, D. Fourer, and H. Maaref, “Neural-enhanced dynamic range compression inversion: A hybrid approach for restoring audio dynamics,” arXiv preprint\narXiv:2411.04337, 2024.\n[5] S. Nercessian, “Neural parametric equalizer matching using differentiable biquads,” in Proc. International Conference on Digital Audio Effects (DAFx20),\n2020.\n[6] J. T. Colonel, C. J. Steinmetz, M. Michelen, and J. D. Reiss, “Direct design of\nbiquad filter cascades with deep learning by sampling random polynomials,” in\nProc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing\n(ICASSP), 2022.\n[7] C. J. Steinmetz, N. J. Bryan, and J. D. Reiss, “Style transfer of audio effects with\ndifferentiable signal processing,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2207.08759, 2022.\n[8] S. Alarie, C. Audet, A. E. Gheribi, M. Kokkolaras, and S. Le Digabel, “Two\ndecades of blackbox optimization applications,” EURO Journal on Computational\nOptimization, vol. 9, p. 100011, 2021.\n[9] U. Zölzer, DAFX: Digital Audio Effects. Chichester, UK: Wiley Online Library,\n2011.\n[10] D. Giannoulis, M. Massberg, and J. D. Reiss, “Digital dynamic range compressor design—a tutorial and analysis,” Journal of the Audio Engineering Society,\nvol. 60, no. 6, pp. 399–408, 2012.\n[11] S. Gorlow and J. D. Reiss, “Model-based inversion of dynamic range compression,”\nIEEE Transactions on Audio, Speech, and Language Processing, vol. 21, no. 7,\npp. 1434–1444, 2013.\n[12] S. H. Hawley, B. Colburn, and S. I. Mimilakis, “Signaltrain: Profiling audio compressors with deep neural networks,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1905.11928, 2019.\n[13] A. Wright, E.-P. Damskägg, and V. Välimäki, “Real-time black-box modelling\nwith recurrent neural networks,” in Proc. International Conference on Digital\nAudio Effects (DAFx19). University of Birmingham, 2019.\n[14] D. Sheng and G. Fazekas, “A feature learning siamese model for intelligent control\nof the dynamic range compressor,” in 2019 International Joint Conference on\nNeural Networks (IJCNN), 2019, pp. 1–8.\n[15] J. Engel, L. Hantrakul, C. Gu, and A. Roberts, “Ddsp: Differentiable digital\nsignal processing,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2001.04643, 2020.\n[16] O. Take, K. Watanabe, T. Nakatsuka, T. Cheng, T. Nakano, M. Goto,\nS. Takamichi, and H. Saruwatari, “Audio effect chain estimation and dry signal recovery from multi-effect-processed musical signals,” in Proc. International\nConference on Digital Audio Effects (DAFx24), 2024, pp. 1–8.\n\n14\n\n\f[17] M. Comunità, C. J. Steinmetz, and J. D. Reiss, “Differentiable black-box and graybox modeling of nonlinear audio effects,” Frontiers in Signal Processing, vol. 5,\np. 1580395, 2025.\n[18] M. A. M. Ramírez, O. Wang, P. Smaragdis, and N. J. Bryan, “Differentiable signal\nprocessing with black-box audio effects,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference\non Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2021, pp. 66–70.\n[19] Y. Gong, Y.-A. Chung, and J. Glass, “AST: Audio Spectrogram Transformer,” in\nProc. Interspeech 2021, 2021, pp. 571–575.\n[20] D. Fourer and G. Peeters, “Objective characterization of audio signal quality:\napplications to music collection description,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on Acoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2017, pp. 711–715.\n[21] N. V. Findler, C. Lo, and R. Lo, “Pattern search for optimization,” Mathematics\nand computers in simulation, vol. 29, no. 1, pp. 41–50, 1987.\n[22] M. A. Gelbart, J. Snoek, and R. P. Adams, “Bayesian optimization with unknown\nconstraints,” arXiv preprint arXiv:1403.5607, 2014.\n[23] R. M. Bittner, J. Salamon, M. Tierney, M. Mauch, C. Cannam, and J. P. Bello,\n“Medleydb: A multitrack dataset for annotation-intensive mir research.” in Proc.\nInternational Society for Music Information Retrieval Conference (ISMIR), 2014,\npp. 155–160.\n[24] S. Groot, Q. Chen, J. C. Van Gemert, and C. Gao, “Cleanumamba: a compact\nmamba network for speech denoising using channel pruning,” in Proc. IEEE ISCAS, 2025, pp. 1–5.\n[25] J. Koo, S. Paik, and K. Lee, “End-to-end music remastering system using selfsupervised and adversarial training,” in Proc. IEEE International Conference on\nAcoustics, Speech and Signal Processing (ICASSP), 2022, pp. 4608–4612.\n[26] T. Kastner and J. Herre, “An efficient model for estimating subjective quality of\nseparated audio source signals,” in Proc. IEEE WASPAA, 2019, pp. 95–99.\n\n15\n\n\f", "numLines": 939, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 939}}}
